{"paragraphs":[{"cues":[{"time":0,"text":"If you haven't ordered yet, I generally find the rigatoni with the spicy tomato sauce"},{"time":7000,"text":"goes best with diseases of the small intestine."}]},{"cues":[{"time":10000,"text":"(Laughter)"}]},{"cues":[{"time":12000,"text":"So, sorry -- it just feels like I should be doing stand-up up here because of the setting."},{"time":16000,"text":"No, what I want to do is take you back to 1854"},{"time":21000,"text":"in London for the next few minutes, and tell the story --"},{"time":25000,"text":"in brief -- of this outbreak,"},{"time":28000,"text":"which in many ways, I think, helped create the world that we live in today,"},{"time":32000,"text":"and particularly the kind of city that we live in today."},{"time":34000,"text":"This period in 1854, in the middle part of the 19th century,"},{"time":38000,"text":"in London's history, is incredibly interesting for a number of reasons."},{"time":42000,"text":"But I think the most important one is that"},{"time":45000,"text":"London was this city of 2.5 million people,"},{"time":48000,"text":"and it was the largest city on the face of the planet at that point."},{"time":53000,"text":"But it was also the largest city that had ever been built."}]},{"cues":[{"time":55000,"text":"And so the Victorians were trying to live through"},{"time":58000,"text":"and simultaneously invent a whole new scale of living:"},{"time":62000,"text":"this scale of living that we, you know, now call \"metropolitan living.\""},{"time":67000,"text":"And it was in many ways, at this point in the mid-1850s, a complete disaster."},{"time":73000,"text":"They were basically a city living with a modern kind of industrial metropolis"},{"time":77000,"text":"with an Elizabethan public infrastructure."},{"time":80000,"text":"So people, for instance, just to gross you out for a second,"},{"time":85000,"text":"had cesspools of human waste in their basement. Like, a foot to two feet deep."},{"time":91000,"text":"And they would just kind of throw the buckets down there"},{"time":94000,"text":"and hope that it would somehow go away,"},{"time":96000,"text":"and of course it never really would go away."},{"time":99000,"text":"And all of this stuff, basically, had accumulated to the point"},{"time":102000,"text":"where the city was incredibly offensive to just walk around in."}]},{"cues":[{"time":106000,"text":"It was an amazingly smelly city. Not just because of the cesspools,"},{"time":110000,"text":"but also the sheer number of livestock in the city would shock people."},{"time":113000,"text":"Not just the horses, but people had cows in their attics that they would use for milk,"},{"time":117000,"text":"that they would hoist up there and keep them in the attic"},{"time":120000,"text":"until literally their milk ran out and they died,"},{"time":122000,"text":"and then they would drag them off to the bone boilers down the street."},{"time":128000,"text":"So, you would just walk around London at this point"},{"time":131000,"text":"and just be overwhelmed with this stench."},{"time":134000,"text":"And what ended up happening is that an entire emerging public health system"},{"time":139000,"text":"became convinced that it was the smell that was killing everybody,"},{"time":143000,"text":"that was creating these diseases"},{"time":145000,"text":"that would wipe through the city every three or four years."},{"time":148000,"text":"And cholera was really the great killer of this period."}]},{"cues":[{"time":150000,"text":"It arrived in London in 1832, and every four or five years"},{"time":155000,"text":"another epidemic would take 10,000, 20,000 people in London"},{"time":159000,"text":"and throughout the U.K."},{"time":161000,"text":"And so the authorities became convinced that this smell was this problem."},{"time":165000,"text":"We had to get rid of the smell."},{"time":167000,"text":"And so, in fact, they concocted a couple of early, you know,"},{"time":170000,"text":"founding public-health interventions in the system of the city,"},{"time":174000,"text":"one of which was called the \"Nuisances Act,\""},{"time":176000,"text":"which they got everybody as far as they could"},{"time":178000,"text":"to empty out their cesspools and just pour all that waste into the river."},{"time":183000,"text":"Because if we get it out of the streets, it'll smell much better,"},{"time":187000,"text":"and -- oh right, we drink from the river."},{"time":191000,"text":"So what ended up happening, actually,"},{"time":193000,"text":"is they ended up increasing the outbreaks of cholera"},{"time":195000,"text":"because, as we now know, cholera is actually in the water."},{"time":199000,"text":"It's a waterborne disease, not something that's in the air."},{"time":202000,"text":"It's not something you smell or inhale; it's something you ingest."}]},{"cues":[{"time":205000,"text":"And so one of the founding moments of public health in the 19th century"},{"time":209000,"text":"effectively poisoned the water supply of London much more effectively"},{"time":213000,"text":"than any modern day bioterrorist could have ever dreamed of doing."},{"time":216000,"text":"So this was the state of London in 1854,"},{"time":220000,"text":"and in the middle of all this carnage and offensive conditions,"},{"time":226000,"text":"and in the midst of all this scientific confusion"},{"time":229000,"text":"about what was actually killing people,"},{"time":232000,"text":"it was a very talented classic 19th century multi-disciplinarian named John Snow,"},{"time":238000,"text":"who was a local doctor in Soho in London,"},{"time":241000,"text":"who had been arguing for about four or five years"},{"time":243000,"text":"that cholera was, in fact, a waterborne disease,"},{"time":246000,"text":"and had basically convinced nobody of this."},{"time":249000,"text":"The public health authorities had largely ignored what he had to say."},{"time":253000,"text":"And he'd made the case in a number of papers and done a number of studies,"},{"time":257000,"text":"but nothing had really stuck."},{"time":259000,"text":"And part of -- what's so interesting about this story to me"},{"time":261000,"text":"is that in some ways, it's a great case study in how cultural change happens,"},{"time":266000,"text":"how a good idea eventually comes to win out over much worse ideas."},{"time":271000,"text":"And Snow labored for a long time with this great insight that everybody ignored."}]},{"cues":[{"time":275000,"text":"And then on one day, August 28th of 1854,"},{"time":280000,"text":"a young child, a five-month-old girl whose first name we don't know,"},{"time":284000,"text":"we know her only as Baby Lewis, somehow contracted cholera,"},{"time":288000,"text":"came down with cholera at 40 Broad Street."},{"time":291000,"text":"You can't really see it in this map, but this is the map"},{"time":294000,"text":"that becomes the central focus in the second half of my book."},{"time":299000,"text":"It's in the middle of Soho, in this working class neighborhood,"},{"time":301000,"text":"this little girl becomes sick and it turns out that the cesspool,"},{"time":305000,"text":"that they still continue to have, despite the Nuisances Act,"},{"time":308000,"text":"bordered on an extremely popular water pump,"},{"time":312000,"text":"local watering hole that was well known for the best water in all of Soho,"},{"time":316000,"text":"that all the residents from Soho and the surrounding neighborhoods would go to."}]},{"cues":[{"time":320000,"text":"And so this little girl inadvertently ended up"},{"time":323000,"text":"contaminating the water in this popular pump,"},{"time":325000,"text":"and one of the most terrifying outbreaks in the history of England"},{"time":331000,"text":"erupted about two or three days later."},{"time":333000,"text":"Literally, 10 percent of the neighborhood died in seven days,"},{"time":337000,"text":"and much more would have died if people hadn't fled"},{"time":339000,"text":"after the initial outbreak kicked in."},{"time":342000,"text":"So it was this incredibly terrifying event."},{"time":344000,"text":"You had these scenes of entire families dying"},{"time":347000,"text":"over the course of 48 hours of cholera,"},{"time":349000,"text":"alone in their one-room apartments, in their little flats."},{"time":354000,"text":"Just an extraordinary, terrifying scene."},{"time":357000,"text":"Snow lived near there, heard about the outbreak,"},{"time":361000,"text":"and in this amazing act of courage went directly into the belly of the beast"},{"time":364000,"text":"because he thought an outbreak that concentrated"},{"time":367000,"text":"could actually potentially end up convincing people that,"},{"time":371000,"text":"in fact, the real menace of cholera was in the water supply and not in the air."},{"time":377000,"text":"He suspected an outbreak that concentrated"},{"time":379000,"text":"would probably involve a single point source."},{"time":383000,"text":"One single thing that everybody was going to"},{"time":385000,"text":"because it didn't have the traditional slower path"},{"time":388000,"text":"of infections that you might expect."}]},{"cues":[{"time":391000,"text":"And so he went right in there and started interviewing people."},{"time":394000,"text":"He eventually enlisted the help of this amazing other figure,"},{"time":398000,"text":"who's kind of the other protagonist of the book --"},{"time":400000,"text":"this guy, Henry Whitehead, who was a local minister,"},{"time":403000,"text":"who was not at all a man of science, but was incredibly socially connected;"},{"time":406000,"text":"he knew everybody in the neighborhood."},{"time":408000,"text":"And he managed to track down, Whitehead did,"},{"time":410000,"text":"many of the cases of people who had drunk water from the pump,"},{"time":413000,"text":"or who hadn't drunk water from the pump."},{"time":415000,"text":"And eventually Snow made a map of the outbreak."},{"time":420000,"text":"He found increasingly that people who drank from the pump were getting sick."},{"time":423000,"text":"People who hadn't drunk from the pump were not getting sick."},{"time":426000,"text":"And he thought about representing that"},{"time":428000,"text":"as a kind of a table of statistics of people living in different neighborhoods,"},{"time":431000,"text":"people who hadn't, you know, percentages of people who hadn't,"},{"time":433000,"text":"but eventually he hit upon the idea"},{"time":435000,"text":"that what he needed was something that you could see."},{"time":437000,"text":"Something that would take in a sense a higher-level view"},{"time":439000,"text":"of all this activity that had been happening in the neighborhood."}]},{"cues":[{"time":442000,"text":"And so he created this map,"},{"time":445000,"text":"which basically ended up representing all the deaths in the neighborhoods"},{"time":449000,"text":"as black bars at each address."},{"time":452000,"text":"And you can see in this map, the pump right at the center of it"},{"time":455000,"text":"and you can see that one of the residences down the way"},{"time":457000,"text":"had about 15 people dead."},{"time":459000,"text":"And the map is actually a little bit bigger."},{"time":461000,"text":"As you get further and further away from the pump,"},{"time":463000,"text":"the deaths begin to grow less and less frequent."},{"time":466000,"text":"And so you can see this something poisonous"},{"time":469000,"text":"emanating out of this pump that you could see in a glance."},{"time":473000,"text":"And so, with the help of this map,"},{"time":475000,"text":"and with the help of more evangelizing"},{"time":477000,"text":"that he did over the next few years"},{"time":479000,"text":"and that Whitehead did, eventually, actually,"},{"time":481000,"text":"the authorities slowly started to come around."},{"time":483000,"text":"It took much longer than sometimes we like to think in this story,"},{"time":486000,"text":"but by 1866, when the next big cholera outbreak came to London,"},{"time":491000,"text":"the authorities had been convinced -- in part because of this story,"},{"time":495000,"text":"in part because of this map -- that in fact the water was the problem."}]},{"cues":[{"time":499000,"text":"And they had already started building the sewers in London,"},{"time":501000,"text":"and they immediately went to this outbreak"},{"time":503000,"text":"and they told everybody to start boiling their water."},{"time":505000,"text":"And that was the last time that London has seen a cholera outbreak since."},{"time":510000,"text":"So, part of this story, I think -- well, it's a terrifying story,"},{"time":513000,"text":"it's a very dark story and it's a story"},{"time":515000,"text":"that continues on in many of the developing cities of the world."},{"time":519000,"text":"It's also a story really that is fundamentally optimistic,"},{"time":522000,"text":"which is to say that it's possible to solve these problems"},{"time":525000,"text":"if we listen to reason, if we listen to the kind of wisdom of these kinds of maps,"},{"time":529000,"text":"if we listen to people like Snow and Whitehead,"},{"time":531000,"text":"if we listen to the locals who understand"},{"time":533000,"text":"what's going on in these kinds of situations."},{"time":536000,"text":"And what it ended up doing is making the idea"},{"time":539000,"text":"of large-scale metropolitan living a sustainable one."}]},{"cues":[{"time":543000,"text":"When people were looking at 10 percent of their neighborhoods dying"},{"time":546000,"text":"in the space of seven days,"},{"time":548000,"text":"there was a widespread consensus that this couldn't go on,"},{"time":551000,"text":"that people weren't meant to live in cities of 2.5 million people."},{"time":555000,"text":"But because of what Snow did, because of this map,"},{"time":557000,"text":"because of the whole series of reforms"},{"time":559000,"text":"that happened in the wake of this map,"},{"time":561000,"text":"we now take for granted that cities have 10 million people,"},{"time":565000,"text":"cities like this one are in fact sustainable things."},{"time":567000,"text":"We don't worry that New York City is going to collapse in on itself"},{"time":570000,"text":"quite the way that, you know, Rome did,"},{"time":572000,"text":"and be 10 percent of its size in 100 years or 200 years."},{"time":575000,"text":"And so that in a way is the ultimate legacy of this map."},{"time":578000,"text":"It's a map of deaths that ended up creating a whole new way of life,"},{"time":583000,"text":"the life that we're enjoying here today. Thank you very much."}]}]}